    base:desc "The digital twin is orchestrated around four core functional blocks: (i) Data acquisition where the low‑level driver streams raw temperature data to a time‑series database; (ii) Simulation models—Model A (two free parameters) and Model B (four free parameters)—which are calibrated on‑demand using the live data; (iii) Algorithms that leverage the calibrated models; notably a Kalman filter that fuses measured temperatures with Model B to estimate the unmeasured heat‑bed temperature and detect anomalies; and (iv) Visualization and control interfaces that expose real‑time dashboards and provide feedback to the Raspberry Pi controller. Co‑simulation enables what‑if scenarios by injecting historical or real‑time PT data into the models to optimise controller parameters. This architecture implements a closed self‑adaptation loop: abnormal plant behaviour triggers automated experiments, re‑calibration, re‑configuration of the Kalman filter, what‑if simulation, and controller retuning, thereby aligning the PT and DT in real time."
]

